Anonymous Sun 07 Jan 2018 07:01:54 No.13379752 Report

>>13379619
You comprehended my exact feel through a wall of pure characters. Well done.

>>13379630
High above the Atlantic Ocean, is a medium sized airliner cut through the thin, high altitude air in the near pitch black darkness outside, a Boeing-767 specifically, painted in a plain white color with a cheery "Oceanic Airlines" logo painted on both sides of the forward fuselage of the wide bodied aircraft, flying on a direct flight to JFK International from Buenos Aires, its position only revealed by the blinking navigational lights around the body and wingtips of the plane, and the plane's transponder.
Holy fuck that's one big run-on sentence. You need to parse that into multiple sentences since you're comma splicing a bunch of complete ones or alternatively use conjunctions or semicolons to connect the clauses. There are also a lot of unnecessary commas (like the very first one). You also used "cut" when you would need "cutting" due to your use of "is." If the action is directly in progress, then you need to conjugate that correctly. When you revise this, make sure that the verbs all line up situationally.
>Captain John Smith glanced over the instrument panel in front of him, and as per usual, their altitude sat a comfortable 40,000 feet, cruising speed at roughly 470 knots, their GPS putting them about 300 kilometers off the coast of the Dominican Republic, and looking back up and out of the cockpit windows, seeing what amounts to perfectly clear skies, excluding some lazy clouds dotting here and there hundreds of feet below them.
Exact same problems. You also need to evaluate word choice METICULOUSLY, as in go through word by word and see if it really needs to be there. Take the first part of the first sentence of the whole thing, you don't need "high altitude" because the audience can infer that. I'm running out of characters, but that should give you a good starting point for revisions.
